#!/bin/sh
# ,mvlink — move a file, then leave a symlink at its old location pointing to
#           the new one.  Essentially `mv SRC DEST && ln -s DEST SRC`, done
#           safely and with a correct link target.
#
# Usage:
#   ,mvlink [-f] [-r] [-p] [mv-options...] SRC DEST     # rename form
#   ,mvlink [-f] [-r] [-p] [mv-options...] SRC... DIR   # move into a directory
#
# By default it refuses to overwrite an existing destination.  Pass -f to
# force: mv is allowed to clobber and any existing SRC is replaced by the link.
# Pass -p to create missing destination directories first (like `mkdir -p`).
# Any *other* leading option (e.g. -v) is forwarded verbatim to `mv`.
#
# The symlink left behind uses an ABSOLUTE target by default, so it keeps
# resolving no matter what your CWD is or how deep SRC was nested.  Pass -r for
# a RELATIVE target instead, which survives relocating SRC and DEST together
# (e.g. moving the whole tree) but breaks if only one of them later moves.
set -eu

prog=${0##*/}

usage() {
    cat >&2 <<EOF
Usage: $prog [-f] [-r] [-p] [mv-options...] SRC DEST
       $prog [-f] [-r] [-p] [mv-options...] SRC... DIR

Moves each SRC to the destination, then creates a symlink at the old SRC
location pointing to the new file.

  -f  force: overwrite an existing destination / replace SRC
  -r  make the symlink target relative instead of absolute
  -p  create missing destination directories (like mkdir -p)

Other leading options (e.g. -v) are forwarded to mv.  Refuses to overwrite an
existing destination unless -f is given.
EOF
}

# Print the path of $1 (target) relative to directory $2 (the link's location).
# Both arguments must be absolute and canonical (as produced by `pwd -P`).
relpath() {
    _t=$1
    _b=$2
    _up=""
    while [ "$_b" != "/" ]; do
        case $_t/ in
            "$_b"/*) break ;;
        esac
        _up="../$_up"
        _b=${_b%/*}
        [ -n "$_b" ] || _b="/"
    done
    if [ "$_b" = "/" ]; then
        _rest=${_t#/}
    else
        _rest=${_t#"$_b"/}
    fi
    if [ -z "$_rest" ]; then
        _up=${_up%/}
        [ -n "$_up" ] || _up="."
        printf '%s\n' "$_up"
    else
        printf '%s\n' "$_up$_rest"
    fi
}

force=0
relative=0
createdirs=0
mvopts=""

# Parse leading options.  -h/-f/-r/-p are ours; anything else starting with '-'
# is forwarded to mv.  '--' ends option parsing.
while [ $# -gt 0 ]; do
    case $1 in
        -h | --help) usage; exit 0 ;;
        -f | --force) force=1; shift ;;
        -r | --relative) relative=1; shift ;;
        -p | --parents) createdirs=1; shift ;;
        --) shift; break ;;
        -*) mvopts="$mvopts $1"; shift ;;
        *) break ;;
    esac
done

if [ $# -lt 2 ]; then
    usage
    exit 1
fi

# Last operand is the destination; everything before it is a source.
eval "dest=\${$#}"
nsrc=$(($# - 1))

# Treat dest as a directory if it exists as one, was written with a trailing /,
# or -p was given with multiple sources (only a directory makes sense then).
dest_is_dir=0
if [ -d "$dest" ]; then
    dest_is_dir=1
else
    case $dest in */) dest_is_dir=1 ;; esac
    if [ "$createdirs" -eq 1 ] && [ "$nsrc" -gt 1 ]; then
        dest_is_dir=1
    fi
fi

if [ "$nsrc" -gt 1 ] && [ "$dest_is_dir" -eq 0 ]; then
    echo "$prog: target '$dest' is not a directory (required for multiple sources)" >&2
    exit 1
fi

# Create missing destination directories up front, if asked.
if [ "$createdirs" -eq 1 ]; then
    if [ "$dest_is_dir" -eq 1 ]; then
        mkdir -p -- "$dest"
    else
        case $dest in
            */*) ddir=${dest%/*}; [ -z "$ddir" ] && ddir=/ ;;
            *)   ddir=. ;;
        esac
        mkdir -p -- "$ddir"
    fi
fi

if [ "$force" -eq 1 ]; then
    mvopts="$mvopts -f"
fi

i=0
while [ "$i" -lt "$nsrc" ]; do
    src=$1
    shift
    i=$((i + 1))

    if [ ! -e "$src" ] && [ ! -L "$src" ]; then
        echo "$prog: '$src' does not exist" >&2
        exit 1
    fi

    if [ "$dest_is_dir" -eq 1 ]; then
        srcbase=${src%/}       # tolerate a trailing slash on SRC
        srcbase=${srcbase##*/}
        target="${dest%/}/$srcbase"
    else
        target=$dest
    fi

    if [ "$force" -eq 0 ] && { [ -e "$target" ] || [ -L "$target" ]; }; then
        echo "$prog: '$target' already exists (use -f to overwrite)" >&2
        exit 2
    fi

    # Move first.  Word-splitting of $mvopts is intentional (forwarded flags).
    # shellcheck disable=SC2086
    mv $mvopts -- "$src" "$target"

    # Resolve the moved file to a clean absolute path (dir canonical, basename
    # appended) for use as the link target.
    case $target in
        */*) tdir=${target%/*}; [ -z "$tdir" ] && tdir=/ ;;
        *)   tdir=. ;;
    esac
    tdir=$(CDPATH= cd -- "$tdir" && pwd -P)
    target_abs="${tdir%/}/${target##*/}"

    if [ "$relative" -eq 1 ]; then
        # Canonical absolute directory that will hold the symlink.  SRC itself
        # is gone now, but its parent directory remains.
        case $src in
            */*) sdir=${src%/*}; [ -z "$sdir" ] && sdir=/ ;;
            *)   sdir=. ;;
        esac
        sdir=$(CDPATH= cd -- "$sdir" && pwd -P)
        linktarget=$(relpath "$target_abs" "$sdir")
    else
        linktarget=$target_abs
    fi

    if [ "$force" -eq 1 ]; then
        ln -sf -- "$linktarget" "$src"
    else
        ln -s -- "$linktarget" "$src"
    fi

    printf '%s: %s -> %s\n' "$prog" "$src" "$linktarget" >&2
done
